EVALUATION of the RESONANCE PARAMETERS of Mn-55 in the ENERGY     2525 1451
RANGE 0 to 122 keV- H. Derrien, L.C. Leal, N.M.Larson, D. Wiarda  2525 1451
K. Guber, and G. Arbanas.                                         2525 1451
                                                                  2525 1451
The resonance parameters were obtained from a sequential Bayes    2525 1451
SAMMY analysis of the most recent experimental neutron            2525 1451
transmissions and capture cross sections in the resolved energy   2525 1451
range: Harvey et al. transmissions measured at ORELA in 1980,     2525 1451
Aerts et al. Capture cross sections measured at GELINA in 2006,   2525 1451
and Guber et al. Capture cross section measured at ORELA in 2007. 2525 1451
For the evaluation in the thermal energy range Widder et al.      2525 1451
(1975) capture cross section, Cote et al. (1964) total cross      2525 1451
sections, and Rainwater et al. (1964) total cross sections were   2525 1451
considered. The thermal capture cross sections were normalized at 2525 1451
the 0.0253 eV value of 13.27 b which is an average of the         2525 1451
available experimental values, consistent with the recent         2525 1451
evaluation of Trkov et al.(2007).  The thermal cross sections     2525 1451
calculated by the resonance parameters are the following:         2525 1451
                                                Res. Int.         2525 1451
                   Capture        13.274 b       13.514           2525 1451
                   Total          15.390 b         -              2525 1451
                   Scattering      2.116 b         -              2525 1451
                                                                  2525 1451
The capture resonance integral is 13.514 b in the energy range    2525 1451
0.5 eV to 120 keV.                                                2525 1451
                                                                  2525 1451
Most of the p-wave resonances are not observed in the experimental2525 1451
transmission data. For those resonances only the capture area     2525 1451
could be obtained with good accuracy.  The capture area is        2525 1451
proportional to   gamman*gammag / gammatot and only the product   2525 1451
gamman*gammag could be defined.  A solution is to assign to all   2525 1451
this resonances a constant capture width value equal to an        2525 1451
estimated averaged value.  In this case the SAMMY fit to the      2525 1451
capture data is generally poor.  The solution of varying both the 2525 1451
capture width and the neutron width in the SAMMY fit has been     2525 1451
chosen is the evaluation.  The resulting capture widths do not    2525 1451
deviate too much from an average value.  The fit is obviously not 2525 1451
unique but give a good description of the experimental data. The  2525 1451
study of the statistical properties of the neutron widths has     2525 1451
shown that the obtained set of parameters is reasonable.          2525 1451
                                                                  2525 1451
Only s-wave and p-wave resonances are given in the evaluation.    2525 1451
However the study of the statistical properties of the p-wave     2525 1451
resonance parameters has shown that 25% of them(the very small    2525 1451
one) could be d-wave resonances. Including these possible d-wave  2525 1451
resonances in the p-wave resonances has a negligible effect on    2525 1451
the calculated capture cross section.                             2525 1451
                                                                  2525 1451
Two components of the capture cross section are given is the      2525 1451
evaluation: the first component is calculated by the observed     2525 1451
resonance parameters; the second component is given as a File 3   2525 1451
background.  This background stands for                           2525 1451
the contribution of the direct capture, for the contribution of   2525 1451
non observed d-wave resonances, and for possible errors           2525 1451
in the calculation of the multiple scattering effect by           2525 1451
SAMMY in the experimental capture cross sections. The estimation  2525 1451
of the average d-wave contribution below 122 keV was obtained from2525 1451
SAMMY/URR.  The error on the experimental background is           2525 1451
important(20% to 30%), contributing to the most part of           2525 1451
the uncertainty on the average capture cross section              2525 1451
                                                                  2525 1451
The following table compares the average capture cross section to 2525 1451
the experimental values of Lerigoleur , and of Garg and Macklin.  2525 1451
The present evaluation is systematically lower than Lerigoleur    2525 1451
(absolute measurement) by 12% on average; part of the discrepancy 2525 1451
could be due to the inaccuracy of the calculation of the d-wave   2525 1451
component in the background file.                                 2525 1451
